{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584399"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:45:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:45:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14466"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14466"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.02,0.04,0.68,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7161"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57223"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7161"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14466"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42682"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"40"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4903"},{"type":"tags","id":"4905"},{"type":"tags","id":"4914"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"8435"},{"type":"tags","id":"9867"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17109"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17132"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57223","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/57223"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following correctly describes venules?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Microscopic blood vessels which drain blood towards capillaries","Blood vessels which contain valves","Macroscopic blood vessels which drain blood towards capillaries","Microscopic blood vessels which drain blood away from capillaries","Macroscopic blood vessels which drain blood away from capillaries"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that venules are \u003Cstrong\u003Emicroscopic blood vessels which drain blood away from capillaries\u003C/strong\u003E. Venules are small blood vessels that collect blood from capillaries and transport it towards larger veins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMicroscopic blood vessels which drain blood towards capillaries\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because this describes arterioles, not venules. Arterioles carry blood from small arteries to capillaries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood vessels which contain valves\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect for venules. While larger veins have valves to prevent backflow of blood, venules typically do not have valves due to their small size and the low pressure of blood flow at this level.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMacroscopic blood vessels which drain blood towards capillaries\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect on two counts: venules are microscopic, not macroscopic, and they drain blood away from capillaries, not towards them.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMacroscopic blood vessels which drain blood away from capillaries\u003C/strong\u003E is partially correct in describing the direction of blood flow but incorrect in classifying venules as macroscopic. Venules are too small to be seen without magnification.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the structure and function of venules is important for comprehending microcirculation, tissue perfusion, and the overall flow of blood through the cardiovascular system.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Venules are microscopic blood vessels that drain blood away from capillaries towards larger veins.","Venules do not have valves, unlike larger veins.","Understanding the structure and function of venules is crucial for comprehending microcirculation and tissue perfusion."],"references":["Gopalan, C., \u0026 Kirk, E. Biology of Cardiovascular and Metabolic Diseases. 2022. Academic Press.","Hemmings, H. C., \u0026 Egan, T. D. Pharmacology and physiology for anesthesia e-book: foundations and clinical application. 2012. Elsevier Health Sciences","Tansey EA, Montgomery LEA, Quinn JG, Roe SM, Johnson CD. Understanding basic vein physiology and venous blood pressure through simple physical assessments. Adv Physiol Educ. 2019 Sep 1;43(3):423-429. doi: 10.1152/advan.00182.2018. PMID: 31408386."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42682"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14466"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42682","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42682"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-25T17:41:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-25T17:42:24+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7161"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"57223"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"40","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/40"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\u2699\ufe0f","name":"Physiology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attri